name: AKK
text:
Over the course of 2019 I have been able to purchase blue corn grits, yellow grits, yellow cornmeal, rolled oats, flax seeds and polenta from McEwen & Sons.

My first order was in February in my last semester of getting my bachelor's degree. At that time I had no time to spend on thinking about meal planning and no money to go out to eat (and not willing to eat ramen), so I decided to take a gamble on a 10lb bag of blue grits instead.

Since then, McEwen & Sons grains have been a fairly large staple of my diet.
At this point, I am mostly gluten free, and not even by conscious decision. The way corn or oatmeal fills up your stomach feels entirely different from the way bread or pasta does - and never have I felt physically ill or lethargic from making and eating a little too much (many?) grits.

For a month or two, I found a local supermarket that offered grits in bulk and thought I'd switch, but despite my attempts to add spices and such they didn't taste like much of anything (they weren't organic and definitely hadn't been refrigerated).
Making cornbread using the recipe on the bag was also wonderful! And very easy to make and pack, though is always best straight out of the oven or with soup.

For anyone trying to eat healthy on a budget - or really anyone who enjoys tasting food at all - I very much recommend McEwen & Sons.

They offer free ground shipping on all orders over $75, which I try to take advantage of, as it's usually around $25 of shipping that I can now spend on provisions instead.

Additionally any orders over $40 include a free gift!
Once it was yellow cornmeal, which got me hooked on that. This most recent order included blue cornmeal, which I haven't tried yet but am very much looking forward to making blue cornbread with).

Current favorite recipe:
1.In a cast iron pan, cover some garlic and shallots with oil/butter/lard and roast in your oven until crispy.
2. Add some grits or cornmeal to boiling water
3. cook on low, stirring until thick.
4. Add chipotle, garlic and shallots, hatch green chile, some buttermilk, coriander, spinach etc.
5. Enjoy

A very long review, but I'm spending Christmas morning alone this year and thought I should give something to somebody this morning.

So long and thanks for all the grits,

AKK

name: Catherine Stephens
text: Having received glasses from this location in the past, as other optical labs in area couldn't get prescription correct, I returned based on prior experience (and price). I picked out a pair of glasses and a pair of lens to be put into one of my frames. I was assured the glasses would be ready at the very latest, without fail, no error, promised before I left for a road trip. I desperately needed new glasses as I work with small numbers all day, and my old glasses had seen better times. I got a call 3 days ago telling me my lenses were in, and they didnt know why the glasses weren't, but I was again promised they would be ready today. I went to pick up glasses, as I leave first thing in the morning for over two weeks working. The lenses were ready. Glasses nowhere to be found. The bottom line, I was given false info. The glasses will be here next week. This does me no good. I am now in an emergency situation, as I cannot see, and have to go to work. A shoulder shrug, sorry was all I got. If a correct pick up time cannot be given, then why bother giving one at all? It doesnt matter at this point, because with a $500 refund, someone else was willing to take my money, give me glasses when promised, I guess someone else needed my business. First time on you, second time on....wait, there wont be a second time.

I am on a fixed income and my money only goes so far and I expect the best for my money. That's why I get meat from Sams.  My advice is to talk to the butcher and fix this. text: Sorry to say after many years of membership we will not be returning, I understand that running a business is difficult lord knows I do. I am sure this message will go on deaf ears at Sams, but really thought someone should know how poorly they treat their customers (yes I made management aware too). We stopped using walmart 5 years ago because of their poor service and it seems the philosophy has moved to Sams. Today my wife was in line only to have the register closed when she was next in line after she had waited a while, she moved to another only to have it closed after she waited a while. The lady on both occasions did not  give a reason or even apologize for the inconvenience. She simply point to the self check out and said  feel free to check yourself out. Well to anyone that knows my wife she is quiet and never gets upset with anyone but me. She walked out and left over $500 of stuff in her buggie. I must agree with her if you pay for the privilege to shop somewhere than you should be serviced like you paid to shop somewhere. Sad to say goodbye Sams Club.
